e “Thick” Literary Journal -- tComposing the Canon: The Individual and the Romantic Aesthetic in the GDR -- tRecalling the Goddess Pandora: From Utopia to Resignation, from Goethe to Peter Hacks in Irmtraud Morgner’s Amanda -- tDistinktionsstrategien im literarischen Feld und 233 Aktualisierung tabuisierter Traditionen in der selbst verlegten Literatur der DDR in den 1980er Jahren0 arestricted accessuhttp://purl.org/coar/access_right/c_16ecfonline access with authorization2star  aFresh perspectives on the cultural history of the German Democratic Republic, exploring the nation's dialogue with the German past.Established, commissioned, and edited by the Department of German at the University of Edinburgh, Edinburgh German Yearbook encourages and disseminates lively and open discussion of themes pertinent to German Studies, viewed from all angles but with particular interest in problems arising out of politics and history. No other yearbook covers the entire field while addressing a focused theme in each issue. Coinciding with the twentieth anniversary of the fall of the Berlin Wall, volume 3 re-directs current debates on memory and tradition, opening up fresh perspectives on the cultural history of the GDR and exploring how the nation's cultural discourses entered into a productive but often problematic dialogue with the values of the past and with the German cultural inheritance. Topics include the compositional engagement with musical heritage; industrial design and cultural politics; the establishment of antifascist monuments and their use as sites of resistance; constructions of a cultural heritage in architecture; the influence of cultural politics on literary scholarship; continuities and breaks with tradition in visualand literary culture; and engagement with the past in the works of Konrad Wolf, Irmtraud Morgner, and Anna Seghers. Contributors: Leonie Beiersdorf, Julian Blunk, Dara Bryant, Helen Finch, Carola Hähnel-Mesnard, StacyHartman, Elaine Kelly, Heather Mathews, Katharina Pfützner, Matthew Philpotts, Larson Powell, Tim Reiß, Marianne Schwarz-Scherer, Laura Silverberg. Matthew Philpotts is Lecturer in German at the University of Manchester, and Sabine Rolle is Lecturer in German at the University of Edinburgh.  aMode of access: Internet via World Wide Web.  aIn English.0 aDescription based on online resource; title from PDF title page (publisher's Web site, viewed 06. Mrz 2024) 0aGerman literaturexHistory and criticismzGermany (East). 0aPolitical culturezGermany (East). 4aEnglish & American Literature. 4aGerman Literature. 7aLITERARY CRITICISM / European / German.2bisacsh  aAnna Seghers.  aAntifascist Monuments.  aCultural Discourses.  aCultural History.  aGerman Democratic Republic.  aIrmtraud Morgner.  aKonrad Wolf.  aLiterary Culture.  aMemory.1 aBeiersdorf, Leonie, econtributor.4ctb4https://id.loc.gov/vocabulary/relators/ctb1 aBlunk, Julian, econtributor.4ctb4https://id.loc.gov/vocabulary/relators/ctb1 aBryant, Dara, econtributor.4ctb4https://id.loc.gov/vocabulary/relators/ctb1 aFinch, Helen, econtributor.4ctb4https://id.loc.gov/vocabulary/relators/ctb1 aGerlach, Sophie A., econtributor.4ctb4https://id.loc.gov/vocabulary/relators/ctb1 aHartman, Stacy, econtributor.4ctb4https://id.loc.gov/vocabulary/relators/ctb1 aHähnel-Mesnard, Carola, econtributor.4ctb4https://id.loc.gov/vocabulary/relators/ctb1 aKelly, Elaine, econtributor.4ctb4https://id.loc.gov/vocabulary/relators/ctb1 aMathews, Heather E., econtributor.4ctb4https://id.loc.gov/vocabulary/relators/ctb1 aPfützner, Katharina, econtributor.4ctb4https://id.loc.gov/vocabulary/relators/ctb1 aPhilpotts, Matthew, econtributor.4ctb4https://id.loc.gov/vocabulary/relators/ctb1 aPhilpotts, Matthew, eeditor.4edt4http://id.loc.gov/vocabulary/relators/edt1 aPowell, Larson, econtributor.4ctb4https://id.loc.gov/vocabulary/relators/ctb1 aReiß, Tim, econtributo